\int\frac{\sin^2(x)}{1 - \tan(x)} dx
\tan(x) = \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}
\dfrac{\cos(x)}{\cos(x)}
\dfrac{\cos(x)+\sin(x)}{\cos(x)+\sin(x)}
\cos(2x) = 1 - 2\sin^2(x)
 u = \sin(x)
t=\tan x
dt=(1+t^2)dx
\sin^2 x=1-\cos^2x=1-\frac1{1+\tan^2x}=\frac{t^2}{1+t^2}
\int\frac{t^2}{(1+t^2)^2(1-t)}dt
I = \int \dfrac{sin^2x}{1 - tanx} dx
J = \int \dfrac{cos^2x}{1 - tanx} dx
I + J = \int \dfrac{1}{1 - tanx} dx
J - I = \int \dfrac{cos^2x - sin^2x}{1 - tanx} dx = \int (cos^2x + sinx\cdot cosx)dx 
